// MRE for tinyC bug: decimal float literal parser accumulates rounding
// error so that 0.75 is parsed as 0x3FE8000000000001 (~0.7500000000000001)
// instead of the exact double 0x3FE8000000000000 (0.75).
//
// Root cause: examples/tinyc/lex.c reads the fractional part by repeatedly
// adding `(digit) * scale` where `scale` starts at 0.1 and is multiplied
// by 0.1 each iteration. Since neither 0.1 nor its powers are exactly
// representable in binary floating-point, the accumulated error pushes
// 0.75 one ulp above the true value.
//
// Downstream symptom (the reason this matters): corec's hashtable uses
// `if (ht->size >= 0.75 * ht->num_buckets) resize();` to decide when to
// grow. For an initially-16-bucket SymbolTable, the threshold should be
// 12 entries, but tinyc's miscompiled comparison evaluates 12 >= 12.0...01
// as false, so the table never resizes. Long probe sequences then cause
// later lookups to spuriously fail (parser_tinyc reports "Undefined SSA
// value" on entries that were inserted earlier).
//
// The fix lives in the lex.c float-literal parser: collect the fractional
// digits as an integer, then perform a single division by the appropriate
// power of ten so that exact values like 0.75 round correctly.
extern int printf(const char *fmt, ...);

int main(void) {
    double x = 0.75;
    // Should print exactly 12.000000... — bug prints 12.000000000000002.
    printf("%.20f\n", x * 16.0);
    if (12 >= x * 16) printf("OK\n"); else printf("FAIL\n");
    return 0;
}
